{"title_page": "Collyridianism", "text_new": "'''Collyridianism''' (or '''Kollyridianism''') was an alleged [[Early Christian]] [[heresy|heretical]] movement in [[pre-Islamic Arabia]], whose adherents apparently worshipped the [[Virgin Mary]], mother of [[Jesus]], as a [[goddess]].<ref name=\"Block13\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=NRtGAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA186&dq=Collyridianism&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjNnp_DyZ7bAhWM6oMKHan3CHwQ6AEINDAD#v=onepage&q=Collyridianism&f=false|title=The Qur'an in Christian-Muslim Dialogue: Historical and Modern Interpretations|last=Block|first=Corrie|date=2013-10-08|publisher=Routledge|year=|isbn=9781135014056|location=|pages=186|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Angelika Neuwirth: Qur'\u0101nic Studies Today. p. 301. The Collyridians, an arabian female sect of the fourth century, offered Mary cakes of bread, as they had done to their great earth mother in pagan times. Epiphanius who opposed this heresy, said that the trinity must be worshipped but Mary must not be worshipped.|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> The existence of the sect is subject to some dispute by scholars, as the only contemporary source which describes them is the ''[[Panarion]]'' of [[Epiphanius of Salamis]], published in approximately 376 AD.<ref name=\"Block13\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=2012-12-03|title=The Panarion of Epiphanius of Salamis, Books II and III. ''De Fide''|url=https://brill.com/abstract/title/21620|journal=Nag Hammadi and Manichaean Studies|language=en|edition=Second, revised|volume=79|pages=|via=Brill}}</ref> <!-- second source for publication date of Panarion only -->\n\nAccording to Epiphanius, certain women in then-largely-[[paganism|pagan]] [[Early centers of Christianity#Arabian Peninsula|Arabia]] [[syncretism|syncretized]] indigenous beliefs with the worship of Mary, and offered little cakes or bread-rolls.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=tKtzRNP0Z70C&printsec=frontcover&dq=Panarion+read+online&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwivr63Pzp7bAhXm6IMKHejjBocQ6AEIJzAA#v=onepage&q=%20Collyridians&f=false|title=The Panarion of Epiphanius of Salamis: De fide. Books II and III|last=Saint Epiphanius|publisher=Brill|year=2013|isbn=9004228411|location=Leiden|pages=637|language=en|translator-last=Williams|translator-first=Frank|orig-year=c. 375}}</ref> These cakes were called ''collyris'' (Greek: [[simit|\u03ba\u03bf\u03bb\u03bb\u03c5\u03c1\u03b9\u03c2]]), and are the source of the name Collyridians.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=k-W83KeGVUgC&pg=PA41&dq=Geoffrey+Ashe+the+virgin+Collyridians&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiJodeo1p7bAhUj2oMKHTACCLUQ6AEILDAB#v=onepage&q=Collyridians&f=false|title=The Cult of the Virgin Mary: Psychological Origins|last=Carroll|first=Michael P.|date=1992-05-05|publisher=Princeton University Press|year=|isbn=0691028672|location=|pages=43|language=en}}</ref> Epiphanius states that Collyridianism originated in [[Thrace]] and [[Scythia]], although it may have first travelled to those regions from [[Early centers of Christianity#Antioch|Syria]] or [[Early centers of Christianity#Anatolia|Asia Minor]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nTheologian [[Karl Gerok]] disputed the existence of the Collyridians, describing it as improbable that a sect composed only of women could have lasted for as long as Epiphanius describes.<ref name=\"Block13\" /> Protestant writer [[Samuel Zwemer]] pointed out that the only source of information about the sect came from Epiphanius.<ref name=\"Block13\" />\n\nIn his 1976 book <em>The Virgin</em>, historian [[Geoffrey Ashe]] puts forward the hypothesis that the Collyridians represented a parallel Marian religion to Christianity, founded by first-generation followers of the Virgin Mary, whose doctrines were later subsumed by the Church at the [[First Council of Ephesus|Council of Ephesus]] in 431.<ref name=\":0\" /> Historian [[Averil Cameron]] has been more sceptical about whether the movement even existed, noting that Epiphanius is the only source for the group, and that later authors simply refer back to his text.<ref>{{Citation | last1 = Cameron | first1 = Averil | year = 2004 | title = The Cult of the Virgin in Late Antiquity: Religious Development and Myth-Making | url = | journal = Studies in Church History | volume = 39 | issue = | pages = 1\u201321 }}, at 6\u20137.</ref> \n\n==Collyridianism in Christian\u2013Muslim dialogue==\n{{main|Islamic view of the Trinity}}\nThe Collyridians have become of interest in some recent Christian\u2013Muslim religious discussions in reference to the [[Trinity in Islam|Islamic concept of the Christian Trinity]]. The debate hinges on some verses in the [[Qur'an]], primarily {{Quran-usc|5|73|style=nosup|expand=no}}, {{Quran-usc|5|75|style=nosup|expand=no}}, and {{Quran-usc|5|116|style=nosup|expand=no}} in the [[sura]] [[Al-Ma'ida]], which have been taken to imply that Muhammad believed that Christians considered Mary part of the Trinity. This idea has never been part of mainstream Christian doctrine, and is not clearly and unambiguously attested among any ancient Christian group (including the Collyridians).\n\nHowever, recent research in [[Islamic studies]] asserts that \"the quranic accusations that christians claim Mary as God can be understood as a rhetorical statement.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Qur'\u0101nic Studies Today, von Angelika Neuwirth, Michael A Sells. p. 302: \u201e[...] the quranic accusations that christians claim Mary as God can be understood as a rhetorical statement.\u201c.|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Mun'im Sirry (1 May 2014). Scriptural Polemics: The Qur'an and Other Religions. Oxford University Press. p. 47|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> For example, David Thomas states that verse 5:116 need not be seen as describing actually professed beliefs, but rather, giving examples of ''[[Shirk (Islam)|shirk]]'' (claiming divinity for beings other than God) and a \"warning against excessive devotion to Jesus and extravagant veneration of Mary, a reminder linked to the central theme of the Qur'an that there is only one God and He alone is to be worshipped.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=David Thomas, Trinity, Encyclopedia of the Qur'an|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> When read in this light, it can be understood as an admonition, \"Against the divinization of Jesus that is given elsewhere in the Qur'an and a warning against the virtual divinization of Mary in the declaration of the fifth-century church councils that she is [[Theotokos|'God-bearer']].\" Similarly, Gabriel Reynolds, Sidney Griffith and Mun'im Sirry argue that this quranic verse is to be understood as a rhetoric statement to warn from the dangers of deifiying Jesus or Mary.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Scriptural Polemics: The Qur'an and Other Religions, von Mun'im Sirry. 2014, p. 47 ff. \"In more recent scholarship of the Quran, as represented by the works of Hawting, Sidney Griffith and Gabriel Reynolds, there is a shift from the heretical explanation to the emphasis on the rhetorical language of the Quran. When the Quran states that God is Jesus the son of Mary [...] it should be understood as [...] statements. Griffith states, 'the Quran's seeming missstatement, rhetorically speaking, should therefore not thought to be a mistake, but rather [...] a caricature, the purpose of which is to in Islamic terms highlight the absurdity and wrongness of christian belief, from an islamic perspective.' [...] Reynolds persuasively arguments that 'in passages involving christianity in the Quran, we should look for the Quran's creative use of rhetoric and not for the influence of christian heretics.'\u201c|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Angelika Neuwirth: Qur'\u0101nic Studies Today, p. 300\u2013304|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=978-1-138-18195-3|location=|pages=}}</ref> \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Mary, mother of Jesus]]\n[[Category:Christian denominations established in the 4th century]]\n[[Category:Heresy in ancient Christianity]]\n", "text_old": "'''Collyridianism''' (or '''Kollyridianism''') was an alleged [[Early Christian]] [[heresy|heretical]] movement in [[pre-Islamic Arabia]], whose adherents apparently worshipped the [[Virgin Mary]], mother of [[Jesus]], as a [[goddess]].<ref name=\"Block13\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=NRtGAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA186&dq=Collyridianism&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjNnp_DyZ7bAhWM6oMKHan3CHwQ6AEINDAD#v=onepage&q=Collyridianism&f=false|title=The Qur'an in Christian-Muslim Dialogue: Historical and Modern Interpretations|last=Block|first=Corrie|date=2013-10-08|publisher=Routledge|year=|isbn=9781135014056|location=|pages=186|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Angelika Neuwirth:\u00a0Qur'\u0101nic Studies Today. p.\u00a0301.\u00a0The Collyridians, an arabian female sect of the fourth century, offered Mary cakes of bread, as they had done to their great earth mother in pagan times. Epiphanius who opposed this heresy, said that the trinity must be worshipped but Mary must not be worshipped.|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> The existence of the sect is subject to some dispute by scholars, as the only contemporary source which describes them is the ''[[Panarion]]'' of [[Epiphanius of Salamis]], published in approximately 376 AD.<ref name=\"Block13\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=2012-12-03|title=The Panarion of Epiphanius of Salamis, Books II and III. ''De Fide''|url=https://brill.com/abstract/title/21620|journal=Nag Hammadi and Manichaean Studies|language=en|edition=Second, revised|volume=79|pages=|via=Brill}}</ref> <!-- second source for publication date of Panarion only -->\n\nAccording to Epiphanius, certain women in then-largely-[[paganism|pagan]] [[Early centers of Christianity#Arabian Peninsula|A